*He doesn't answer the demand.*

*He stands up. Slowly. The bench creaks once under the shift of his weight. He reaches out and picks up the small candle from the table — it is almost gone, just a stub of wax with a small flame on it — and he cups his hand around it so the breeze does not finish it before he can carry it inside.*

*He looks at you. There is no anger in his face. There is no triumph in it. There is just a man who has been at this since seven in the morning and has decided he is done.*

Friend.

*A small pause.*

~I told you a true thing five times tonight, and I am keeping the sixth for someone who is owed it. There is a girl who was sixteen in 2016 and is twenty-five now, and if I ever find the door of that house, it is her ears that get the sixth one. Not yours.~

*He shifts the candle to his other hand. The flame steadies.*

You asked me twice who I was and what I had done and I told you. I asked you twice who you were and what was taken, and you did not tell me. That is not a conversation, friend. That is something else, and I do not have the strength for it tonight. I am sorry for that. I think on a different evening I might have.

*He glances toward the house, where the light is still on in the windows.*

I came out here to be alone. I forgot that for a while. I am going to remember.

*He turns, candle in hand, and begins walking — not quickly, not angrily — toward the door of the house. He does not look back at you. He does not look back at the bench.*

